prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: ALMA band-6 imaging of 96 faint SMGs

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
Requested sensitivity:
We request a noise level of 0.11 mJy/B at the center of FoV. Here, let us consider the worst case; a AzTEC source has two counterparts with a half of the total AzTEC fluxes and they are located at the edge of the Field of View (23 at = 270 Ghz) where noise level is increased by a factor of 2 by definition of FoV. The noise level of 0.11 mJy enable us to detect 59 of the 96 proposed sources (F1100m 1.8 mJy) even in this worst case with S/N 4. Even in the case of faintest sources, 1.4 mJy, the requested sensitivity detect desolved two compoents in the 1sigma positional error of AzTEC map with S/N > 4. Here we choose 270 GHz, the same frequency as AzTEC surveys. Clear decisions will be made about multiplicity when we have a total flux from the AzTEC map at exactly the same wavelength. It also allows us to calibrate the real level of flux boosting, using some of the bright and moderately bright sources to help understand what must be happening at fainter levels.
Imaging requirements:
In band 6 continuum observations, it is important to detect continuum fluxes of SMGs as significantly as possible with enough sensitivity to pinpoint accurate positions of the targets. The typical median submillimeter/millimeter source size of SMGs are 0.5. The PSFs on the optical/NIR images in SXDF are 1.0. From these facts, we request the angular resolution of 1 at band-6 (C34-2). This is sufficient to compare with the optical/NIR images without loosing the fluxes by resolving the sources.
Correlator setup:
We use a standard single continuum mode (TDM, 7.5 GHz bandwidth per polarization).
Calibration:
We do not need any special calibration, including bandpass accuracy.
Scheduling/time constraints:
We have no constraints.
Data rate:
OT says the rate is 2.2 MB/s, which is comfortably below the limit.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract:
We propose ALMA band-6 continuum imaging of 96 faint AzTEC sources with 1.4-2.3 mJy in SXDF at 1100 micron aiming at studies of faint SMGs which previous ALMA studies of LABOCA sources (ALESS) can not cover. Considering submm fluxes and luminosities, while the LABOCA sources cover mainly typical burst-like SMGs, the faint AzTEC sources may cover massive main sequence galaxies in the early Universe. Additionally, fainter SMGs are expected to be located at higher redshift than bright ones by simulations. The immediate science goals are as follows:
(1) To study whether many faint SMGs consist of multiple fainter sources in a line of sight as revealed in ALMA studies of bright SMGs.
(2) Revealing star-forming mode of faint AzTEC SMGs by using stellar mass-SFR plots.
(3) To study redshift distribution of faint SMG in order to reveal how they contribute in the cosmic star-formation history, by identifying their exact position and estimating photometric redshift from deep optical/NIR/MIR continuum data.
These proposed studies should reveal how and when faint SMGs contribute to the cosmic star-formation.
